segments.text: And the CETTI building, room 801.
This is September the 15th.
Chances look good, maybe for a shower.
And I have the pleasure of chatting with Charlie Wooten about his experiences here as a member of the faculty and staff, the administration.

To begin with, to introduce yourself to anyone who might listen to this tape or read the transcription, describe your background in high school and where you grew up and what folks did and so forth before you came to work here at A&M.
Okay.
I grew up in Kimmel County, which is County Cities Junction.
After a few years in small schools like Teacup and London,

transferred when I finally got a bus system and from the fifth grade on I went through school at Junction riding the bus 15 or so miles each way every day but I had a good experience with it I graduated from there in 1943 immediately tried to go into the service at that time I was 16 and the
decided that was a little young.
So when I turned 17, in October, that year, I tried again to get into the that time I had, I was one of five brothers.
The other four were already in service.
And one of them was flying B-24s at the time out of Tarrant Field in Fort Worth.
I'd gone up to visit with him.
And at that time, they were still in the

Macho era with the watch silk scarf around the neck and all that and I thought that was the greatest thing I'd ever seen So I decided I wanted to get in the Air Force I tried to enlist in the Air Force and went through all of the examinations and all and in the federal building in San Antonio, they told me that Okay, I took all the quizzes to come back in two weeks, I believe and they let me know how I came out I did
I came back in two weeks, and they said, well, you passed everything.
Everything is just fine.
Said, you will be accepted into the Air Force.
And I wanted to go on a pilot training.
I said, great.
When do I go?
They said, well, we can't take you.
You're only 17.
We can't take you till you're 18.
Well, I was just quite discouraged by it.
So I was walking down the hall.
As I recall, it was on the third floor of the federal building.
As I was going down the hall, I ran into this cat standing next to an open doorway in a pair of dress blue uniforms with all the gold stripes up and down the arm, Marine Corps recruiting officer.
He said, what's the matter son, wouldn't they take you down there?
I said, oh no, they'll take me, but I have to wait until I'm 18 before I can go in.
He said, well, come in here and talk to me.
And I said, oh, no, I'm not interested in that.
I want to fly.
He said, haven't you ever heard of the Marine Air Force?
I said, well, really, not much.
He said, we've got the greatest air corps in the world.
I said, well, it doesn't make any difference to me whether it's the Army Air Corps or the Marine Air Corps.
I just wanted to fly.
He said, tell you what to do.
You come in here, and we'll fill out these recruiting papers.
We get through with this.
I'm going to write down on the bottom of it that it says, you know everybody has to go through boot camp at the Marine Corps.
I said, oh yeah, I don't mind that.
He said, well, as soon as you get out of boot camp, I'm going to write on here that they're sending you to college training school.
Fine.
Sign it up.
I was almost through boot camp before I found out they didn't even have a
a pilot training program.
They got all their pilots out of the Navy.
Which was probably the best thing that ever happened to me because I found out I got air sick and all that sort of thing.
So most things that have happened to me in life that were discouraging at the time turned out to be a whole lot better than they looked like they were going to be.
I spent some two and a half years in the South Pacific and the last nine months I spent in China.
At the end of the war, we were on an LST going back from Okinawa to Guam to refit to go into Japan.
That was the plan at the moment.
On the way back to Guam, they dropped the bomb.
When we landed in Guam, they said, okay, we're going to refit now.
Rather than going to attack Japan, we're going to repatriate the Japanese Army out of North China.
that had been there since 1937.
Hold on just a second.
How did you and your buddies hear the news of the bomb, and what was your reaction to it?

We were on an LST, which is not the easiest thing to be on in the South Pacific, particularly since about that time we were not too far off the island of Truk, which is one of their big air bases, and a typhoon came up and started blowing us toward Truk.
So the LST has a flat tank deck on the bottom, which we all were on cots and sleeping on it.
The seas were so rough that it would buckle those plates.
And a lot of the cots, when they went up, came down, break the legs off of them, so we slept on the floor.
It was a very rough passage.
We heard about it.
At first, we didn't believe it, because we, well, these sorts of things come across, and they're really not so.

But then we got confirmation, and everybody was extremely relieved and thought whatever it took, that was the greatest thing that could have happened because we were really not looking forward to having to go into the Japanese mainland, which we understood.
Now, I was a private, so I did not know the grand strategy of the war effort.
but even at that level we knew that it was going to be a very, very tough landing if we did go into Japan.
So it, as I say, it was a great relief.
Everybody was extremely happy about it.
We couldn't wait to get to Guam and get a cold beverage there if we could and then get everything refitted and head out to China.
So you're on Guam when you hear the war is over?
No, we were still on the way to Guam.
They signed the, on the USS Missouri, they signed the, I said decapulation, the treaty that ended the war.
But of course, everyone really thought that when they dropped the bomb that the war would be over in a matter of days, which it really was.
I've forgotten, it was August the
You probably know the dates, but I don't remember exactly what it was.
But we refitted in Guam, loaded up, and said this was the first early part of August.
So we moved real quickly and landed in, moved into Tencent, China, and landed there on the Ohio River on September the 1st of 19...
That would have been 1944 or 45.
Spent about nine months there.
We repatriated the Japanese army, got them all disarmed.
Primarily the concern was that when the Chinese learned that the war was over that they would massacre the whole army.
There was not a great big number of Japanese there because they had all the arms and so forth.

We repatriated them out of there, and by that time, Chiang Kai-shek was coming down, Mao Tse-tung was coming down from Siberia and coming into China, and they were having the wars between Chiang Kai-shek and Mao Tse-tung, and we were also put into guarding the Shenzhen-Peking Railroad.

uh which was a vital link then in the for the nationalist armies but uh we got uh finished well we got pulled out of there never did get finished we finally sort of gave up on being peacekeepers and uh came back in uh july of that uh 46 and uh finished up the art the marine corps tour and uh
A friend and I, in fact, our next door neighbor lived on the adjoining ranch when I was growing up.
We had a small farm and ranch operation in Kemmel County.
And our next door neighbor named Jarvis, Jack Jarvis, and I went to school together.
He was a year ahead of me in high school.
But he was in the 11th Marines and I was in the 3rd Corps.
We were together in China for most of those nine months.
We both decided then that what we needed to do when we got out was go get an education.
And both of us had come out of a small country school, and we didn't know a thing about what schools were what, which ones we should be interested in attending.
We knew that we had to go to a state school.
We couldn't afford anything else.
We knew there would be a GI bill that would help us through.
So we decided together that, well, it came down between University of Texas and Texas A&M.
So we were in a bar one night and decided, well, we need to make up our minds where we're going to go.
We said, OK, let's flip a coin.
Head, heads, U-T, tails, this is A&M.
Tales came up and we said, OK, there's where we're going.
And so that was that was the great decision making that we did in great evaluation of all the options.
Now, how far in advance of coming over here was that flip?
Oh, that was about a month before we left.
That had been in about June of 46.
And we got back.
He got a little ahead of me.
He was already home when I got home in August.
But from August until the first of September when school started here.
And how did you get from home over here?
Did you have a car?
No.
I was going to be surprised if you did.
No, we neither had a car.
So we, of course, we did have a sea bag.
That's what we lived in for the last two or three years.
So we each packed our sea bags up and got out and hitchhiked.
Came down here and came into
College Station, first time we'd ever been here or seen anything about it.
We were quite, quite surprised really to see what was here.
What did you bring in the sea bag?
We brought our, primarily our, our work clothes are from the, from the Marine Corps, plus tried to, didn't have a suit, of course, didn't really need a suit down here, but
Tacky pants and the shirts and shaving gear, and that was about it.
I mean, we didn't fill up a whole sea bag full of it.
Didn't have much.
No radio, no... What kind of razor?
Safety razor?
Yeah, a safety razor.
One of those straight-edge safety razors.
I never did get the hang of running one of those deadly ones.
What was your impression of the campus when you first saw it?
It was sort of quite impressive, really, because we had not seen any campus like this, so we didn't really know what to expect.
We were sort of quite confused as to where to go and what the next step was going to be.
Of course, we overwhelmed, as a group of returning veterans, we overwhelmed A&M.
We were in the biggest class they'd ever had here at that time.
in the class of 1950, and of course they had no place for us to sleep.

We didn't know that at the time, and by the time we'd finally gotten through registration and asked, all right, now where do we, you know, what dorm do we go to and all this sort of thing, he said, well, there'll be a truck come by here in a little bit that'll pick you up and take you out to the old Brown Air Force Base, and your quarters will be out there.
So we waited, and the truck came by, a big flatbed truck.
We threw our sea bags on there, and we got off 100 miles out in the sticks away from everywhere.
And here was the old Bryan Air Force Base that still had their tar paper shacks up, and we were assigned to one of those tar paper shacks.
Was that at all similar to a boot camp?
We said, we have already been through this.
So let's just
forget about this and go home.
Well, it was about dark by that time.
It had taken all day to get all this done.
And we said, well, we'll at least spend the night.
And we did.
And of course, I'm sure A&M has affected a whole lot of people that same way.
After you spend a little time here, your whole attitude changes about it.
And next morning, things were all right.
And about as you look back on that group of freshmen,
about how many of them were veterans, or what percentage?
TASCAL, I don't remember what percentage, but of the freshman class, my guess would be that we were 75% of the freshman class.
And I presume some of them were a bit older than you.
Some of them may have served the whole war.
Some had.
Now, what I'm talking about now is the ones that
the veterans that came back versus the ones that went directly into the Corps.
And of course, we were not in the Corps at Bryan Air Force Base, but they had enough capacity to handle the normal group on the Corps students.
But we had, yeah, we had a number of them that had been in that served six years or five and six years in the military in various places.
Describe getting...

settled in how did you how did they put you in this barracks instead of that one how did they break you down by groups and so forth somebody in their infinite wisdom had made up a list and your name was on this list to go in and they did this while we were registering you were assigned already assigned to a barrack out at ground air force base and so when the moon was out they dropped us off there i forgot what the uh
It seems like those barracks would hold, oh, 18 to 24 people in it.
Not great big tar paper.
And they were actually tar paper.
One floor.
One floor.
Cots or bunks?
Bunks.
They had steel bunks.
They had double.
And not very large.
But they did have mass quarters for us and other facilities there.
Classrooms were not elaborate at all.
I took chemistry, which of course has a big lab requirement to it, freshman chemistry, which I was scared to death of coming out of a little school.
And it was out there?
It was out there.
All of our classes were out there.
We didn't have any classes in here.
Right.
Now, you all officially were not in the Corps?
No.

uh did did you pick up a nickname quickly oh yes what were y'all uh well we were the we were the uh well we were the vets now i later joined the court when i got after we had gotten through our sophomore year we had the option then of going into the corps without having to go through freshman and sophomore life and i had
seeing how officers lived and how privates lived.
And I said, if there's going to be another one, I know which side I want to be on.
So I joined the Corps, and we had the EVET Air Force.
We had a wing.
But back to that first year, all of you guys that were not in the Corps were nicknamed vets.
That was not a put-down word.
That was a...
A compliment of any.
And there were maybe, how many of you out there?
Oh, there were more than that.
Oh.
I'd say there were close to 2,000 out there.
It was a big group out there.
2,000 veterans?
Veterans.
And were the other?
That's a guess.
What about the regular, what about the plain ordinary freshmen?
Were they out there yet?
No, they were in here.
They were here.
Yeah.
Because later they would be.
Because they were in the Corps.
Yeah.
Later the Corps freshmen would be out there, but not this year.
And all of your courses were out there.
And were these veterans only freshmen?
Yes.
Yeah, I think they were all freshmen.
As far as I can recall, there were no upperclassmen that had been a year or two before they'd done in the service.
How did you register for your classes?
The two most embarrassing things I've ever gone through is a physical in the Marine Corps and registration at Texas A&M.
It was, you know, just...
from this line to the next line to the next line.
And you forgot to do this here, so you had to go back and do it over again here.
And it was not very well organized, the mechanics of it, the structure of it.
But you went through and selected your classes.
What were you then planning to major in?
At that time, I was an undeclared major.
And of course, A&M didn't really require
and you do commit to a major at the beginning of the year.
I finally decided after taking a couple of chemistry courses that I'd be better off in economics.
Do you remember what you took that first year, first semester?
First semester, I took English, took math 101, I believe it was, took chemistry 101,
I took a general science course that they taught at that time.
I'm not sure exactly what it was called.
But I took 18 hours, which was the norm.
Describe a typical class day's routine.
Got up at what hour and did what all?
Well, first thing, we had a mess hall where we ate.
And they had hours for breakfast, so if you wanted breakfast, you had to get there by 7 o'clock, I think.
But we were all used to that anyway from the background, so that wasn't really a problem for anyone.
And we had no transportation.
There was, in our group, in fact, in our group, these were sort of in clusters of those tar paper shacks.
about four or five in each one, and I think in our cluster there was one automobile and one motorcycle.
That was a total transportation system.
But we'd get up, go to breakfast.
There were not bugle calls or anything like that in the military.
It was all, you were on your own to meet your classes, and of course they had all classes at a different time.

spread it out as likely that on campus you take english first or chemistry or whatever there we had it on your schedule to meet the the requirements of the profits you had up there and we had a couple of good props up there uh who were some of those faculty members you remember now uh just uh dr hedges one uh what was the guy's name that taught chemistry he was a
He was a great coyote hunter.
Wasn't John Beckham.
No, I knew John.
Was Happy Harry Hurth out there yet?
No, I had a class under him later on here at Earl Rudders and Systems in public speaking one time.
And y'all were meeting in barracks buildings, those classes.
Yeah.
They had some permanent buildings as well, you know, the church, the chapel, and they had several others that had been built.
In fact, they had a couple of buildings that had been built and probably never been occupied between the time they were built and the time they closed the base.
All right, so you went to class pretty well all morning, ate lunch.
What did you do in the afternoon when you hadn't any time?
It wasn't scheduled.
We had our own baseball games, touch football.
We organized.
I don't think there was much central organization, but each group sort of organized.
We put together groups for you competing with the different outfits out there, much like you did in...
and would have done had you been in here on campus, I assume.
But I don't remember too much about the extracurricular activities.
We had a swimming pool that was still open at that time, a nice swimming pool out there.
Was there a place to see a movie?
Yes, there was a movie house and you had those at the evening and they were, as I recall, most of them were free.
Every once in a while you had one you had to pay for, but as I recall most of them were
were free movies.
And did the GI Bill pay for all of that?
Yes.
As far as you remember?

As far as I remember, they paid for all of your books, all of your tuition, and you didn't really, and fees, and you didn't, and then I think you got $75 a month in addition to that, which... That paid for... That paid for everything else that we had.
And it did.
It paid for everything that we had to have.
Where, how did you travel if you wanted to go from the, okay, so there wasn't a regular bus running from there to town or the campus?
No.
There was really no, no incentive for us to come into campus.
They were sort of operated as two separate units, as best as I could tell from that time, but if you wanted to come to town, you hitchhacked and it was not hard to do.
Everybody would pick you up.
I mean, anybody pick up
What did you older veterans do on Saturday night for a good time?
Well, we went to the usual places that 18, 20-year-old kids go through.
There was an Onyx out there in that neighborhood.
Remember the Onyx?
No, that's before me.
What did it offer?
It was a beer joint.
Okay.
And...
Had a couple of restaurants out there that were just set up for that purpose and then closed up.
But you had opportunities to go, and you could always catch a ride into town.
Was there any gambling over there?
I know it wasn't legal, but was there a... Not there.
Now, there was a place over on the river.
Okay, that's what I was meaning.
Yeah, that there was gambling over there.
I never had the confidence and my skills at gambling to go into one, to really get involved in one of those.
All right, for drinking in those days, Brazos County supposedly offered only beer.
Right.
Were there any places near there to buy, this side of the river, to buy anything stronger?
Not on this side of the river, but we were off close to the river.
So we just went?
You just had to hop across the river, of course, and there was two joints right across the river that had booze.
All right, and if you came into town, into Bryan, where were the attractive places?
The, well, the ones that, oh gosh, the one out on Welburn, what is now Welburn.
Oh, Uncle Ed's.
Uncle Ed's over there.
They had Arnold's.
Barbecue.
Barbecue place over here.
There was, the old Texan was here, by the way.
The drive-in.
Drive-in.
He had the Texan, and there was another drive-in down there.
There's a name I can't remember, not too far from the Texan.
But those were the recreationals, evening recreational spots on the weekends.
Then back on the, what did y'all call it?
Was it the base or the what?
Yeah, we called it the base primarily.
That was the gut of the base.
Back on the base, there was a swimming pool, a theater.
Was there a pool hall?
No, no.
So...
Nothing...

nothing really organized other you know sort of what those things that you can take care of yourself except for the movement how serious were you and your colleagues about doing your studies very serious uh primary concern and we had uh some pretty strict uh in in-house rules that uh
You had a study period that you didn't do a lot of horsing around because people wanted to study and get the heck out of here, you know, make their grades and be sure that they didn't bust out.
And we lost a few kids.
Some were very ill-prepared coming in, even more so than I was.
You studied there in your little barracks?
In the barracks, primarily.
And how often did you go home?
I'd go home three or four times a year.
Again, it was hitchhike.
Did you go that first fall, you remember?
Yeah, I went home once that fall.
How long did it take to hitchhike to Kerrville, I mean to a junction?
You could get there if you left, say, at noon on Friday.
You could get there by midnight that night, 12 hours.
There's really no problem hitchhiking.
Well, I've had a pretty few problems, but, you know, get stranded sometimes.
Share some plus or minus stories about Aggie hitchhiking.

Well, you know, you had the, here around the campus, and we had one out there, you had the hitchhiking benches where definite protocol existed, and you didn't duck the line unless you were, you know, somebody came by and was going to your hometown, well, they'd let you go right from
get in front of the line to pick that one up because it was so convenient.
But anything headed in your direction, generally you took that, and then you took some various routes of going from here to Junction.
There's not a great deal, we didn't have I-10 then, so not a great deal of roadways going there.
So Austin to Fredericksburg to... Austin to Fredericksburg or Kerbel.
Going through Kerbel and going up that way.
Going into...

junction uh generally speaking uh i could get uh i could get to junction and then catch a ride from there out to gate to the ranch and walk from there on into the house now you'd really you didn't wear an aggie uniform because you weren't in the corps did you ever use a sign we did at times yeah aggie sign and uh which was very helpful but uh

During those periods, of course, now, I would hate to have to hitchhike anywhere, but then, particularly, you was either a veteran or a returning veteran, so everybody really was happy to pick you up and take you with them as far as they were going.
Share the most positive story you can remember in your own hitchhiking and the most negative.
Start with the negative.
I was going home one time.
This was just before Christmas.
This time I happened to be, catch a ride over to, uh, going to Kerrville.
I wasn't, the first one wasn't going, but I was going in that direction.
So I ended up going to Kerrville and they let me out of Kerrville and it was already dark.
I was got a late start and things weren't working.
It started drizzling rain, a nasty day, nasty evening.
So I found a fella that was going, I would happen to be in a little bar restaurant thing and, uh,
The guy in there was handing the jukeboxes, collecting the money and putting the stuff in, and he was also helping himself to the beer every chance he got.
So he was going through Junction on the way out to Sonora and said, you know, would you be happy for me to go with him if you'd like?
I asked him how far he was going.
He said, well, he's going all the way to Sonora.
I said, well, I was going to Junction if I could.
I didn't mind if I could.
and ride with him.
Oh, yeah, I'd be happy to have him.
At that time, he'd had several.
By the time he got through stopping, before we got out of Curville, I asked him if I could drive, and he said,
